# Plan: Add JWT Authentication to Express API

## Context
The Express API has no authentication. All write routes are unprotected and accept `userId` from the request body. `tests/auth.test.ts` already exists and specifies the exact expected behavior: registration, login, JWT-protected write operations, and 403 ownership enforcement. `jsonwebtoken` is already installed. No bcrypt/argon2 is available — passwords stay plaintext (tests only test users registered during the test run, not seed users). Vitest runs each test file in an isolated worker with its own in-memory DB copy, so no cross-file state contamination.

---

## Files to Create

### 1. `src/middleware/authenticate.ts`
Three responsibilities: export the JWT secret, augment `express.Request` globally, and export the `authenticate` middleware.

```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";

export const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

// Augment Express Request globally (safe because this file has imports, making it an ES module)
declare global {
  namespace Express {
    interface Request {
      user?: { id: number; username: string };
    }
  }
}

export function authenticate(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction): void {
  const header = req.headers.authorization;
  if (!header || !header.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "No token provided" });
    return;
  }
  const token = header.slice(7);
  try {
    const payload = jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET) as { id: number; username: string };
    req.user = payload;
    next();
  } catch {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid token" });
  }
}
```

### 2. `src/routes/auth.ts`
```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
import { users, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { JWT_SECRET } from "../middleware/authenticate.js";

const router = Router();

// POST /auth/register
router.post("/register", (req, res) => {
  const { username, email, password } = req.body;
  if (!username || !email || !password) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "username, email, and password are required" });
    return;
  }
  if (users.find(u => u.username === username)) {
